    <article class="blog-post">
      <div class="container">
        <p>Power surges can damage or destroy sensitive electronics, appliances, and even hardwired devices in your home. Whole-home surge protection provides a first line of defense—installed at the main panel to catch surges before they reach your circuits.</p>
        <h2>What Causes Power Surges?</h2>
        <p>Surges can come from outside sources like lightning and utility switching, or from within your home when large appliances cycle on and off. Air conditioners, refrigerators, and other motor-driven devices are common internal surge sources.</p>
        <h2>How Whole-Home Surge Protection Works</h2>
        <p>A whole-home surge protector is installed at the main electrical panel. When a voltage spike exceeds the normal range, the device clamps the excess voltage and redirects it safely to ground—before it reaches your outlets, wiring, or connected devices.</p>
        <h2>What It Protects</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>Smart home devices and automation systems</li>
          <li>Televisions, computers, and entertainment systems</li>
          <li>HVAC systems and thermostats</li>
          <li>Refrigerators, dishwashers, and washers/dryers</li>
          <li>EV charger electronics</li>
        </ul>
        <h2>Point-of-Use vs. Whole-Home Protection</h2>
        <p>Power strips with surge protection offer point-of-use protection for individual devices, but whole-home protection provides broader coverage at the source. The two work best together—whole-home protection at the panel plus quality surge strips for high-value electronics.</p>
        <h2>When to Add Surge Protection</h2>
        <p>Surge protection is a smart addition during any panel upgrade, when you install an EV charger, or when you're adding sensitive electronics to your home. It's a relatively modest upgrade with potentially significant protection value.</p>
        <h2>Next Steps</h2>
        <p>Whole-home surge protection can be added as part of a panel upgrade or as a standalone installation. To learn more about panel upgrades, see our <a href="/panel-upgrades">panel upgrades page</a>.</p>
